climbs.name: Whispers
climbs.fa: FA (TR): Todd Swain 04-2012  FA (lead): Todd Swain, Brock Wagstaff, Harrison Hood 04-2012

content.description:
Begin about six feet left of

Mumbles

at a grainy crack/ right facing corner. This crack is near the uphill (left) end of the pillar that sits in front of the main face.

Climb the grainy crack/corner to the top.
content.protection: Carry a standard JT rack. Medium to large cams and a cordelette are needed to rig a TR.
content.location:
Begin about six feet left of

Mumbles

at a grainy crack/ right facing corner. This crack is near the uphill (left) end of the pillar.

climbs.name: Roman Pretzel
climbs.fa: Todd Swain and Alan Roberts, Dec. 1988

content.description: a fun mix of stems, jams, and overhanging face moves in a steep dihedral
content.protection: standard rack
content.location: at the left end of the face above and left from the Mel Cracks

climbs.name: Rock & Roll Girl
climbs.fa: Alan Nelson, Dec. 1981

content.description: This is a short, mediocre climb with hand jamming and recessed fist jams.
content.protection: standard rack
content.location: near the center of the face above and left from the Mel Cracks, and to the right of Modern Jazz

climbs.name: Right Mel Crack
climbs.fa: Kevin Powell, Mike Waugh & Darryl Nakahira, April 1983

content.description:
A good climb with a fierce little crux.

After a few opening moves the crux arrives all too soon; from a good small wire placement, execute very iffy lie-away moves to gain a slot, small cam. From here good holds lead to a welcome rest and re-group. Small wires help with the confidence on a tricky high-step sequence that comes next. The crack now relents (large cam), so take a deep breath and enjoy.
content.protection: Small wires, small cams, large cam. Bolt anchor.

climbs.name: The Power of Now
climbs.fa: 2016 Shawn Scott/ Dino Banco

content.description: Small cams in the patina and a tricky traverse left gets you to the first bolt. Pull the small roof on a nut placement ,clip another bolt and your at the crux. Big reach and a funky hold gets you to the anchors.
content.protection: Small cams/ nuts/ 3 bolts / Anchor.
content.location: To the far left of the I Love Brian Piccolo route.

climbs.name: Piranha
climbs.fa: FA Dino Banco/Shawn Scott. FFA Matt Hagny

content.description: Fire past four bolts on steep rock up to a crack. Place gear and do some very pumpy moves to the jug. More gear leads to the top.
content.protection: 4 bolts / mixed gear. Anchors
content.location: To the right of Hurly Burly.

climbs.name: Pell Mel
climbs.fa: Dino Banco/ Shawn Scott

content.description: Thin edges to gain a lieback off a big block.  From there, more thin edges to another juggy lieback.  Another bit of spice before rounding out to slabbier climbing, but still interesting.
content.protection: 5 bolts, and  a cam  or two a few feet above the first bolt.
content.location: Between Roman Pretzel and Modern Jazz.  Rap rings at top.

climbs.name: Overheard
climbs.fa: FA (TR): Todd & Donette Swain, Teresa Malone 1993  FA (lead): Todd & Donette Swain 04-2012

content.description:
Go up and left on a series of blocks. When the blocks end, make a tricky move up and left onto a ledge. Continue up and left (V1) on a flake, until you can reach right to a bolt. Clip the bolt and make steep moves up a short crack to the top.

Variation 1: Starting either on

Other Voices

or this route, climb the steep huecos just left of the upper portion of the

Other Voices

crack.
content.protection: Carry some tiny gear for the tricky move down low, a hand-sized cam for the flake, and a quickdraw for the bolt. Medium cams and a cordelette are needed to rig a TR.
content.location:
Start in the same spot as

Other Voices

, at the bottom right of a series of blocks that lead up and left.

climbs.name: Other Voices
climbs.fa: Kevin Powell and Darryl Hensel, April 1983

content.description:
Walk to the right around from the Mel Cracks, this climb is the last significant crack system before the crag peters out.

A steep route.

Ledges lead to the meat of the climb, a steep fingers to hand crack (small cam) which is followed to a nice hand-rail below the final bulge (comforting medium cam). Stepping left to good holds seems like the right thing to do, then head up from here. Sling a boulder for the belay.
content.protection: Small and medium cams, sling a boulder for the anchor.

climbs.name: Mutterers
climbs.fa: Todd & Donette Swain, Chris Jones, Brock Wagstaff, Harrison Hood, et al  04-2012

content.description:
Start about 10 feet right of

Other Voices

and

Murmurs

at a left slanting finger crack under a ceiling (V1).

Finger traverse up and left in the crack to a ledge (5.8). Climb the obvious, grainy, parallel cracks above the ledge to the top (5.8).

Variation 1: Climb the left facing flake/corner that is just right of

Murmurs

and about eight left of the regular start of this climb. This start is 5.5 or 5.6.
content.protection: Carry a standard JT rack.
content.location: Start about 10 feet right of Other Voices and Murmurs at a left slanting finger crack under a ceiling.

climbs.name: Murmur Has It
climbs.fa: Todd & Donette Swain, Simeon Heimowitz, Adele  03-2012

content.description:
Start just right of

Other Voices

below a face that leads to an arching flake/ceiling.

Climb up the face to the flake. Go up and left on the flake a bit, then face climb up to the top.
content.protection: Carry a standard JT rack.
content.location:
Start just right of

Other Voices

below a face that leads to an arching flake/ceiling.

climbs.fa: FA (TR): Todd Swain 04-2012

content.description:
Start about 30 feet up and left of

Overheard

at the right edge of a pillar that sits in front of the main face.

Climb the grainy crack on the main face that is at the right (downhill) edge of the pillar.
content.protection: TR
content.location:
Start about 30 feet up and left of

Overheard

at the right edge of a pillar that sits in front of the main face.

climbs.name: Modern Jazz
climbs.fa: Alan Nelson and Karl Mueller, Dec. 1981

content.description: This is a fairly nice thin crack and steep face.  The crux start is hard to protect
content.protection: standard rack
content.location: near the center of the face above and left from the Mel Cracks

climbs.name: Mel's Mantles
climbs.fa: Craig Kain, 1990

content.description:
Many mantles, pretty steep with good edging.

A great alternative after you've burned your forearms with Mel's left and right laps.

Mels Diner is an awesome spot to close the day. Easy access and great landing area.
content.protection: Medium cams for toprope anchor.

climbs.name: Kickin' Bach
climbs.fa: (TR) Karl Mueller & Alan Nelson, 12/81, FL: unknown

content.description:
Walk to the left around from the Mel Cracks and boulder hop to the bottom of the upper left tier. The climb is on the right-hand side, a flakey looking crack in a vertical seam that ends before the top, with another crack located up and to the right.

Steepness on spikes (small cam early please) with the odd jam leads to the end of the first crack and a good rest. Traverse right and climb the well featured crack to the mother of all jugs.
content.protection: Small cams, wires, medium cams for anchor.

climbs.name: I Love Brian Piccolo
climbs.fa: Todd Gordon, Quinn McCleod & Brian Sillasen, 9/86

content.description:
Located on an upper tier buttress to the right of boulder piles. A flaky looking crack that leads to a notch. It can be combined with "Other Voices".

Boulder-hop across from the top of "Other Voices" to find another steep one. Start up a thin crack (cams) to the right of a large thick undercling flake, this leads to a traverse left to the bottom of the main crack. The crack leans leftwards, a big sharp handrail (medium cam in crack) allows you to gain the crack, and good holds and exposed climbing leads to a rest on a large flake on the right. Step left from here and into the crux (small/medium cam) strenuous moves lead to a tricky finish.

Scramble off to the right.
content.protection: Small to medium cams, medium cam anchor.

climbs.name: Left Mel Crack
climbs.fa: Darryl Nakahira, Alan Roberts, Kevin Powell & Mike Waugh, April 1983

content.description:
This is the righthand crack.

A fun climb full of very cool moves.

Good little slots lead to the first impasse; a rather ominous bulge. Good technique pays dividends here and soon the next impasse is reached. Cool high step moves will pull you through this to the last impasse, a thought-provoking but not difficult mantle.

Pull over the top to a medium cam anchor.
content.protection: Small wires, small cams, medium cams for anchor.

climbs.name: Hurly Burly
climbs.fa: Dino Banco/Shawn Scott

content.description: Steep best describes Hurly Burly. Climbs like a sport route but takes gear.
content.protection: Mixed cams up to a #3, nuts, 1 bolt.
content.location: To the far left of other voices

climbs.name: Fusion Punk
climbs.fa: unknown

content.description: Tough start up a steep ringlock-sized straight-in crack along the right side of an "X" marked downward pointing block.  Heed that warning.  The block might feel solid when first reaching up to touch its bottom pointy end, but the entire massive block flexes if pulled at when level with the "X" mark. Above all that, work up the same crack system to the top.
content.protection: Pro to 3", gear anchor.
content.location: Rap via bolted rap anchor atop Pell Mel.

climbs.name: The Fifth Dimension
climbs.fa: Dino Banco/ Shawn Scott

content.description: Hard to reach gear in a thin crack is needed to pull the off the ground crux. Above that a little more gear gets you established under the overhang. Clip two bolts and mixed cams on overhanging rock before the pump sets in. Traverse left at the top and exit same as Power Of Now. Shares anchors with Power Of Now.
content.protection: Small gear at the start/medium cams and two bolts.
content.location: To the right of Power Of Now.

climbs.name: Earworm
climbs.fa: Todd Swain 04-2012

content.description:
Begin about 20 feet left of

Overheard

at the base of a steep, slightly left leaning crack. This is just to the right of some blocks that form a small corridor at the base of the cliff.

Climb the crack system past a wide spot to an anchor.
content.protection: Carry a standard JT rack. Rappel or lower from the anchor.
content.location:
Begin about 20 feet left of

Overheard

at the base of a steep, slightly left leaning crack. This is just to the right of some blocks that form a small corridor at the base of the cliff.

climbs.name: Bleu Plate Especial
climbs.fa: Todd & Donette Swain, Terry English, Nancy Geismar, George Hurley

content.description: Climb up a short, right leaning crack then pull past a bulge to a ledge. Climb the steeper, sculptured face above to the top.
content.protection: Gear to a blue or purple Camalot to protect the route and medium to large cams and some slings to rig an anchor.
content.location: Start about 30 feet to the right (toward Quail Springs) of the Mel Cracks at the next face. There is a large acacia (cat's claw) bush in front of the face.

climbs.name: Background Noise
climbs.fa: Todd & Donette Swain 03-2012

content.description:
Start to the right of

Mutterers

at the next crack.

Climb the crack to a ledge, then climb the short face above to the top.
content.protection: Carry a standard JT rack.
content.location:
Start to the right of

Mutterers

at the next crack.
